<div class="twin-plane work-plane"><h3>Work plane</h3><div class="plane-track"><i class="track-signal"></i><div class="plane-stage" id="work-1">Clear need</div><div class="plane-stage" id="work-2">Stable steps</div><div class="plane-stage" id="work-3">Rules-led decision</div><div class="plane-stage" id="work-4">Visible outcome</div></div></div><div class="twin-links"><i></i><i></i><i></i><i></i></div><div class="twin-plane assurance-plane"><h3>Assurance plane</h3><div class="plane-track"><i class="track-signal"></i><div class="plane-stage" id="assure-1">Named owner</div><div class="plane-stage" id="assure-2">Bound authority</div><div class="plane-stage" id="assure-3">Logged evidence</div><div class="plane-stage" id="assure-4">Active monitoring</div></div></div><div class="twin-readout"><div class="readout-copy"><strong id="model-state">Synchronized for scale</strong><span id="model-explain">Use automation where process stability, control evidence, and ownership support a durable standard.</span></div><div class="sync-meter" aria-hidden="true"><i></i><i></i><i></i><i></i></div></div></div></div></div></div></section>
<section class="section section-mist"><div class="section-inner"><div class="kicker">Portfolio decision architecture</div><h2>Choose the operating mode before choosing the tool.</h2><table class="decision-table"><thead><tr><th>Decision</th><th>Use when</th><th>What must be true</th><th>Primary evidence</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><span class="decision-tag">Redesign</span><br><strong>Fix the process first</strong></td><td>Exceptions and handoffs dominate the work.</td><td>Root causes, decision rights, and process boundaries are made explicit.</td><td>Exception patterns, rework, queue age, ownership gaps.</td></tr><tr><td><span class="decision-tag">Assist</span><br><strong>Keep judgment visible</strong></td><td>Human interpretation or member context materially affects the decision.</td><td>Automation supports preparation, retrieval, routing, or recommendation without obscuring authority.</td><td>Override reasons, review agreement, handling quality, employee adoption.</td></tr><tr><td><span class="decision-tag">Automate</span><br><strong>Execute bounded rules</strong></td><td>Rules, inputs, exceptions, and fallback paths are stable.</td><td>Control mapping, logs, monitoring, ownership, and recovery are built in.</td><td>Cycle time, first-pass quality, exception rate, control completeness.</td></tr><tr><td><span class="decision-tag">Standardize</span><br><strong>Scale a proven pattern</strong></td><td>A solution repeatedly performs across comparable workflows.</td><td>Reuse boundaries, maintenance ownership, platform economics, and retirement criteria are explicit.</td><td>Realized value, reuse effort, incident pattern, adoption retention.</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section>
<section class="section"><div class="section-inner"><div class="kicker">Automation value scorecard</div><h2>A business case that survives contact with operations.</h2><p class="section-intro">The scorecard does not manufacture a maturity number. It names the evidence categories that allow BPM leaders, risk partners, process owners, and platform teams to make the same decision from the same facts.</p><div class="score-line"><strong>Member value</strong><span>Which friction, delay, repetition, or uncertainty changes?</span><em>Evidence: service outcome, wait/cycle time, complaint or repeat-contact signal.</em></div><div class="score-line"><strong>Employee flow</strong><span>What work becomes easier, safer, or more focused?</span><em>Evidence: touches, rework, queue age, exception burden, adoption.</em></div><div class="score-line"><strong>Control quality</strong><span>Does the automation make authority and evidence more legible?</span><em>Evidence: control coverage, traceability, exception closure, monitoring.</em></div><div class="score-line"><strong>Economics</strong><span>Is value tied to a credible baseline and total operating cost?</span><em>Evidence: labor hours avoided, cycle time, quality cost, platform/maintenance burden.</em></div><div class="score-line"><strong>Learning and reuse</strong><span>What becomes a standard, and what remains workflow-specific?</span><em>Evidence: reuse effort, change latency, repeated failure modes, retirement decision.</em></div></div></section>
<section class="section section-dark" id="evidence"><div class="section-inner"><div class="kicker">Verified transfer evidence</div><h2>Built where process, technology, and accountability meet.</h2><div class="proof-river"><div class="proof-row"><div class="date">2025 - present</div><div class="marker"></div><div><strong>Vape-Jet - Director of Operations</strong><p>Leads AI-first operating transformation across production, purchasing, quality, customer success, support, engineering issue flow, Odoo, Jira, HubSpot, Slack, telemetry, and AI-assisted workflows.</p><small>Transfer: cross-functional workflow integration, operating signals, standard work, coaching, and accountable adoption.</small></div></div><div class="proof-row"><div class="date">2017 - present</div><div class="marker"></div><div><strong>DudeWorth - Founder / AI and Automation Advisor</strong><p>Develops opportunity frameworks that assess value, feasibility, data readiness, governance, adoption burden, reuse, and time-to-value; designs agentic workflows with human judgment and escalation.</p><small>Transfer: portfolio selection, automation business cases, governance rails, evaluation, and human authority.</small></div></div><div class="proof-row"><div class="date">2014 - 2018</div><div class="marker"></div><div><strong>Amazon - Operations Management / Site Leader</strong><p>Led launch and execution for Amazon Prime Pittsburgh in a 24/7 environment supporting approximately five million second-day orders annually, with Lean/Gemba routines, visibility, escalation, and standard work.</p><small>Transfer: high-volume operating mechanisms, fact-based prioritization,